# Design Guidance

## Core Principles

### Avoid Generic Slides

Do not create plain bullet lists on white backgrounds. Every slide should feel intentionally designed.

### Use a Topic-Specific Color Palette

Choose colors that match the subject matter. If the same palette works equally well for unrelated topics, it is probably too generic.

### Establish Visual Hierarchy

* One dominant color should carry 60–70% of the visual weight
* Use 1–2 supporting colors
* Reserve a strong accent color for emphasis

### Maintain Consistent Visual Motifs

Pick one reusable design element and repeat it throughout the deck, such as:
* Rounded image frames
* Colored icon circles
* Thick side borders
* Consistent card treatments

### Consider a "Sandwich" Structure

A common pattern:
* Dark title slide
* Light content slides
* Dark conclusion slide

Or commit fully to a dark theme for a premium look.

## Suggested Color Palettes

| Theme | Primary | Secondary | Accent |
|---|---|---|---|
| Midnight Executive | #1E2761 | #CADCFC | #FFFFFF |
| Forest & Moss | #2C5F2D | #97BC62 | #F5F5F5 |
| Coral Energy | #F96167 | #F9E795 | #2F3C7E |
| Warm Terracotta | #B85042 | #E7E8D1 | #A7BEAE |
| Ocean Gradient | #065A82 | #1C7293 | #21295C |
| Charcoal Minimal | #36454F | #F2F2F2 | #212121 |
| Teal Trust | #028090 | #00A896 | #02C39A |
| Berry & Cream | #6D2E46 | #A26769 | #ECE2D0 |
| Sage Calm | #84B59F | #69A297 | #50808E |
| Cherry Bold | #990011 | #FCF6F5 | #2F3C7E |

## Slide Layout Ideas

Every slide should contain a meaningful visual element:
* Images
* Charts
* Icons
* Shapes
* Diagrams

Avoid text-only slides.

### Common Layout Patterns

* Two-column layouts
* Icon + text rows
* 2×2 or 2×3 grids
* Half-bleed image layouts
* Overlay text on imagery

### Effective Data Presentation

* Large statistic callouts
* Side-by-side comparisons
* Timelines and process flows
* Numbered sequences

### Visual Polish

* Icons inside colored circles
* Accent typography
* Consistent spacing
* Intentional whitespace

## Typography

### Recommended Font Pairings

| Header Font | Body Font |
|---|---|
| Georgia | Calibri |
| Arial Black | Arial |
| Calibri | Calibri Light |
| Cambria | Calibri |
| Trebuchet MS | Calibri |
| Impact | Arial |
| Palatino | Garamond |
| Consolas | Calibri |

### Recommended Sizes

| Element | Size |
|---|---|
| Slide title | 36–44 pt bold |
| Section header | 20–24 pt bold |
| Body text | 14–16 pt |
| Captions | 10–12 pt |

### Spacing Guidelines

* Minimum margins: 0.5"
* Gap between content blocks: 0.3"–0.5"
* Leave adequate breathing room
* Avoid overfilling slides

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

* Repeating the same layout on every slide
* Center-aligning body text
* Weak size contrast between headings and body copy
* Defaulting to generic blue palettes
* Inconsistent spacing
* Styling only a few slides while leaving others plain
* Creating text-only slides
* Forgetting text box padding
* Using low-contrast text or icons
* Overly narrow text boxes causing awkward wrapping

### Important

Never use decorative accent lines under slide titles. This is a strong indicator of low-quality AI-generated slides.

Use whitespace, typography, or color blocking instead.

# QA Process (Required)

Assume the first render contains issues.
Your job is to actively find and fix them.

## Content QA

### Extract and Review Text

```bash
python -m markitdown output.pptx
```

Check for:
* Missing content
* Typos
* Incorrect slide order
* Formatting issues

### Detect Placeholder Content

```bash
python -m markitdown output.pptx | grep -iE "xxxx|lorem|ipsum|this.*(page|slide).*layout"
```

If any results appear, remove or replace them before finalizing.

## Visual QA

### Required Workflow

Convert slides to images and inspect them visually.

### Convert Slides to Images

```bash
python scripts/office/soffice.py --headless --convert-to pdf output.pptx
pdftoppm -jpeg -r 150 output.pdf slide
ls slide-*.jpg
```

Note:
* slide-1.jpg for decks under 10 slides
* slide-01.jpg for 10–99 slides
* slide-001.jpg for 100+ slides

Use the exact filenames returned by ls.

### Visual Inspection Checklist

Look for:
* Overlapping elements
* Text overflow or clipping
* Misaligned decorative elements
* Footer collisions
* Uneven spacing
* Elements too close together
* Insufficient margins
* Inconsistent alignment
* Low-contrast text or icons
* Excessive text wrapping
* Leftover placeholders

### Suggested Review Prompt

```
Visually inspect these slides. Assume there are issues — find them.

Look for:
- Overlapping elements
- Text overflow
- Alignment problems
- Uneven spacing
- Low contrast
- Placeholder content
- Clipping or cutoff text

For each slide, report all issues found, including minor ones.
```

### Verification Loop

1. Generate slides
2. Convert to images
3. Inspect carefully
4. List issues
5. Fix issues
6. Re-render affected slides
7. Re-check for new problems

Do not declare success until at least one full fix-and-verify cycle is complete.

### Re-Render Individual Slides

```bash
pdftoppm -jpeg -r 150 -f N -l N output.pdf slide-fixed
```

Replace N with the slide number.

