	('c304c0bd-248c-4bc4-b66c-61047b7471c2', '6e295e2c-7c1c-48b8-a43f-5c4f0b870d1e', 'sevt_01QHbFnZrvqVJY4xkSBwADqX', 'agent.message', '{"id": "sevt_01QHbFnZrvqVJY4xkSBwADqX", "type": "agent.message", "content": [{"text": "Great question! Let me blend up the key insights on oil price movements for you! 🥤\n\n## Current Oil Price Snapshot\n\n", "type": "text"}, {"text": "As of May 8, 2026, oil was priced at $104.07 per barrel using Brent as the benchmark, up $3.62 compared with yesterday morning and around $40 higher than the price one year ago.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "\n\n## Recent Price Changes\n\nThe oil market has been quite volatile recently:\n\n- ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Crude Oil fell to 94.68 USD/Bbl on May 8, 2026, down 0.14% from the previous day. Over the past month, Crude Oil''s price has fallen 3.26%, but it is still 55.16% higher than a year ago.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "\n\n- ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "On May 4, 2026, oil sold for $115.01 per barrel, approximately a $55 rise over the past year.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "\n\n- ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "By May 7, 2026, oil had reached $100.45 per barrel, which was $6.07 less than it cost the previous morning and about $38.90 above its price a year earlier.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "\n\n## What''s Driving These Changes?\n\nThe major factor squeezing prices right now is geopolitical tension: ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "WTI crude oil futures fell 7% to around $95 per barrel this week as President Donald Trump said the ceasefire with Iran remained in place despite fresh clashes between US and Iranian forces. Oil markets remain focused on Hormuz, which has been effectively closed since late February, disrupting global crude flows and forcing production shutdowns across the region.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "\n\n", "type": "text"}, {"text": "The International Energy Agency warned the conflict is removing around 14 million barrels per day from global supply.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "\n\n## Looking Ahead\n\n", "type": "text"}, {"text": "The U.S. Energy Information Administration expects Brent crude oil prices to increase from an average of $81/b in Q1 2026 to a peak of $115/b in Q2 2026 before gradually falling to an average of $88/b in Q4 2026, based on the assumption that the conflict does not persist past April and that traffic through the Strait of Hormuz gradually resumes.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "\n\nThe market remains pressurized by Middle East tensions, but there''s hope that diplomatic efforts could help ease supply concerns! 🍊", "type": "text"}], "processed_at": "2026-05-10T04:23:13.893Z"}', '2026-05-10 04:23:13.893+00', '2026-05-10 04:23:14.384873+00'),
