	('4d096839-8ad2-4aab-ba96-b712797fef2b', 'd022dc04-b668-4da9-b8b6-8f42754bb87e', 'sevt_01WiKPkYvEveTUmPxsXu58FP', 'span.model_request_end', '{"id": "sevt_01WiKPkYvEveTUmPxsXu58FP", "type": "span.model_request_end", "is_error": false, "model_usage": {"input_tokens": 5, "output_tokens": 99, "cache_read_input_tokens": 7944, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 115}, "processed_at": "2026-05-10T05:32:05.623Z", "model_request_start_id": "sevt_01FFGCxrPzQTV1CcLMnC4mY3"}', '2026-05-10 05:32:05.623+00', '2026-05-10 05:32:09.091243+00'),
	('603d9f75-8e0c-4b57-96f7-db18ae631c86', 'd022dc04-b668-4da9-b8b6-8f42754bb87e', 'sevt_01AYm5Gc2oRKmJyLHrmqVUjL', 'agent.tool_result', '{"id": "sevt_01AYm5Gc2oRKmJyLHrmqVUjL", "type": "agent.tool_result", "content": [{"text": "1\t---\n2\tname: xlsx\n3\tdescription: >\n4\t  Use this skill whenever a spreadsheet file is the primary input or output.\n5\t  \n6\t    Trigger when the user wants to:\n7\t    - Open, read, edit, repair, clean, analyze, or format spreadsheet files\n8\t    - Create a new spreadsheet from scratch or from other data sources\n9\t    - Add formulas, charts, tables, pivots, or formatting\n10\t    - Convert between .xlsx, .xlsm, .csv, and .tsv formats\n11\t    - Restructure messy tabular data into a usable spreadsheet\n12\t  \n13\t    Especially trigger when the user references a spreadsheet file by name or path,\n14\t    even casually (e.g. “the xlsx in my downloads”).\n15\t  \n16\t    The final deliverable must be a spreadsheet file.\n17\t  \n18\t    Do NOT trigger when the primary deliverable is:\n19\t    - A Word document\n20\t    - An HTML report\n21\t    - A standalone Python script\n22\t    - A database pipeline\n23\t    - A Google Sheets API integration\n24\t---\n25\t\n26\t# XLSX Creation, Editing, and Analysis\n27\t\n28\t## Core Requirements\n29\t\n30\t### Professional Formatting\n31\t- Use a consistent professional font unless the user specifies otherwise\n32\t  - Preferred: Arial or Times New Roman\n33\t- Maintain clean spacing and alignment\n34\t\n35\t### Zero Formula Errors\n36\tAll delivered Excel models must contain:\n37\t- No `#REF!`\n38\t- No `#DIV/0!`\n39\t- No `#VALUE!`\n40\t- No `#N/A`\n41\t- No `#NAME?`\n42\t\n43\t### Preserve Existing Templates\n44\tWhen editing existing workbooks:\n45\t- Match the workbook''s existing style and conventions exactly\n46\t- Preserve established formatting patterns\n47\t- Do not impose new formatting standards unless requested\n48\t- Existing template conventions override these guidelines\n49\t\n50\t---\n51\t\n52\t# Financial Model Standards\n53\t\n54\t## Color Coding Conventions\n55\t\n56\tUnless overridden by the workbook template or user instructions:\n57\t\n58\t| Purpose | Format |\n59\t|---|---|\n60\t| Hardcoded inputs | Blue text (RGB 0,0,255) |\n61\t| Formulas/calculations | Black text (RGB 0,0,0) |\n62\t| Internal worksheet links | Green text (RGB 0,128,0) |\n63\t| External workbook links | Red text (RGB 255,0,0) |\n64\t| Key assumptions | Yellow fill (RGB 255,255,0) |\n65\t\n66\t## Number Formatting\n67\t\n68\t| Type | Standard |\n69\t|---|---|\n70\t| Years | Text format (`2024`, not `2,024`) |\n71\t| Currency | `$#,##0` |\n72\t| Percentages | `0.0%` |\n73\t| Multiples | `0.0x` |\n74\t| Negative numbers | `(123)` not `-123` |\n75\t| Zeros | Display as `-` |\n76\t\n77\tExamples:\n78\t- Currency: `$#,##0;($#,##0);-`\n79\t- Percentages: `0.0%;(0.0%);-`\n80\t\n81\tAlways include units in headers:\n82\t- Example: `Revenue ($mm)`\n83\t\n84\t---\n85\t\n86\t# Formula Construction Rules\n87\t\n88\t## Assumptions\n89\t- Store assumptions in dedicated cells\n90\t- Reference assumption cells in formulas\n91\t- Never hardcode assumptions inside formulas\n92\t\n93\tCorrect:\n94\t```excel\n95\t=B5*(1+$B$6)\n96\t```\n97\t\n98\tIncorrect:\n99\t```excel\n100\t=B5*1.05\n101\t```\n102\t\n103\t## Formula Quality Checks\n104\t* Verify all references\n105\t* Avoid off-by-one errors\n106\t* Keep formulas consistent across periods\n107\t* Test zero and negative-value edge cases\n108\t* Avoid unintended circular references\n109\t\n110\t## Hardcoded Input Documentation\n111\tDocument all hardcoded assumptions or imported values.\n112\t\n113\tFormat:\n114\t```\n115\tSource: [System/Document], [Date], [Reference], [URL if applicable]\n116\t```\n117\t\n118\tExamples:\n119\t* Source: Company 10-K, FY2024, Page 45\n120\t* Source: Bloomberg Terminal, 8/15/2025\n121\t* Source: FactSet, 8/20/2025\n122\t\n123\t---\n124\t\n125\t# Python Workflow Guidance\n126\t\n127\t## Recommended Libraries\n128\t\n129\t| Library | Best Use |\n130\t|---|---|\n131\t| pandas | Data analysis, cleaning, bulk operations |\n132\t| openpyxl | Formatting, formulas, Excel-specific editing |\n133\t\n134\t## CRITICAL: Use Excel Formulas\n135\tAlways write calculations as Excel formulas.\n136\tDo NOT calculate values in Python and hardcode results.\n137\t\n138\tIncorrect:\n139\t```python\n140\ttotal = df[''Sales''].sum()\n141\tsheet[''B10''] = total\n142\t```\n143\t\n144\tCorrect:\n145\t```python\n146\tsheet[''B10''] = ''=SUM(B2:B9)''\n147\t```\n148\t\n149\tThe workbook must remain dynamic and recalculate correctly when source values change.\n150\t\n151\t## Standard Workflow\n152\t1. Load or create workbook\n153\t2. Modify data, formulas, and formatting\n154\t3. Save workbook\n155\t4. Recalculate formulas\n156\t5. Validate and fix errors\n157\t\n158\t## Mandatory Formula Recalculation\n159\t\n160\tUse:\n161\t```bash\n162\tpython scripts/recalc.py output.xlsx\n163\t```\n164\t\n165\tThe script:\n166\t* Recalculates formulas using LibreOffice\n167\t* Detects Excel errors\n168\t* Returns structured JSON output\n169\t* Works on Linux and macOS\n170\t\n171\tLibreOffice setup is handled automatically.\n172\t\n173\t---\n174\t\n175\t# Common Excel Operations\n176\t\n177\t## Read Excel with pandas\n178\t```python\n179\timport pandas as pd\n180\t\n181\tdf = pd.read_excel(''file.xlsx'')\n182\tall_sheets = pd.read_excel(''file.xlsx'', sheet_name=None)\n183\t```\n184\t\n185\t## Write Excel with pandas\n186\t```python\n187\tdf.to_excel(''output.xlsx'', index=False)\n188\t```\n189\t\n190\t## Creating Excel Files with openpyxl\n191\t```python\n192\tfrom openpyxl import Workbook\n193\tfrom openpyxl.styles import Font, PatternFill, Alignment\n194\t\n195\twb = Workbook()\n196\tws = wb.active\n197\t\n198\tws[''A1''] = ''Hello''\n199\tws[''B1''] = ''=SUM(B2:B10)''\n200\t\n201\tws[''A1''].font = Font(bold=True)\n202\tws[''A1''].alignment = Alignment(horizontal=''center'')\n203\t\n204\twb.save(''output.xlsx'')\n205\t```\n206\t\n207\t## Editing Existing Workbooks\n208\t```python\n209\tfrom openpyxl import load_workbook\n210\t\n211\twb = load_workbook(''existing.xlsx'')\n212\tws = wb.active\n213\t\n214\tws[''A1''] = ''Updated''\n215\tws.insert_rows(2)\n216\t\n217\twb.save(''modified.xlsx'')\n218\t```\n219\t\n220\t---\n221\t\n222\t# Formula Verification Checklist\n223\t\n224\t## Essential Checks\n225\t* Verify sample references before scaling formulas\n226\t* Confirm correct column mappings\n227\t* Remember Excel uses 1-based indexing\n228\t\n229\t## Common Pitfalls\n230\t* Null/NaN handling\n231\t* Wrong sheet references\n232\t* Division by zero\n233\t* Missing referenced cells\n234\t* Incorrect far-right column mapping\n235\t\n236\t## Testing Strategy\n237\t* Start with a few cells\n238\t* Verify dependencies\n239\t* Test edge cases:\n240\t    * Zero values\n241\t    * Negative values\n242\t    * Large values\n243\t\n244\t---\n245\t\n246\t# Interpreting recalc.py Output\n247\t\n248\tExample:\n249\t```json\n250\t{\n251\t  \"status\": \"success\",\n252\t  \"total_errors\": 0,\n253\t  \"total_formulas\": 42\n254\t}\n255\t```\n256\t\n257\tIf errors exist:\n258\t```json\n259\t{\n260\t  \"status\": \"errors_found\",\n261\t  \"error_summary\": {\n262\t    \"#REF!\": {\n263\t      \"count\": 2,\n264\t      \"locations\": [\"Sheet1!B5\"]\n265\t    }\n266\t  }\n267\t}\n268\t```\n269\t\n270\t---\n271\t\n272\t# Best Practices\n273\t\n274\t## openpyxl\n275\t* Excel indexing is 1-based\n276\t* Use data_only=True only when reading calculated values\n277\t* Saving a workbook opened with data_only=True removes formulas\n278\t* Use read_only=True for large reads\n279\t* Use write_only=True for large writes\n280\t\n281\t## pandas\n282\t* Specify dtypes when needed\n283\t* Limit columns for large files\n284\t* Parse dates explicitly\n285\t\n286\tExample:\n287\t```python\n288\tpd.read_excel(\n289\t    ''file.xlsx'',\n290\t    dtype={''id'': str},\n291\t    parse_dates=[''date'']\n292\t)\n293\t```\n294\t\n295\t---\n296\t\n297\t# Code Style\n298\t\n299\t## Python Code\n300\t* Keep code concise\n301\t* Avoid unnecessary comments\n302\t* Avoid redundant variables\n303\t* Avoid excessive print statements\n304\t\n305\t## Excel Models\n306\t* Add comments for complex formulas\n307\t* Document assumptions\n308\t* Add notes for key calculations\n", "type": "text"}], "is_error": false, "tool_use_id": "sevt_011T3bgxU7n39sRw6pGJLRgQ", "processed_at": "2026-05-10T05:32:08.960Z"}', '2026-05-10 05:32:08.96+00', '2026-05-10 05:32:13.89001+00'),
