	('76aa2def-a09b-4294-a883-8f097f0d1f76', '7e900716-2bec-4758-a757-d1d0dd31b316', 'sevt_017NcPG2VmBcEaVy1Dad8htj', 'agent.tool_use', '{"id": "sevt_017NcPG2VmBcEaVy1Dad8htj", "name": "bash", "type": "agent.tool_use", "input": {"command": "ls /mnt/session/uploads/ && ls /workspace/skills/pptx/"}, "processed_at": "2026-05-10T20:55:45.373Z", "evaluated_permission": "allow"}', '2026-05-10 20:55:45.373+00', '2026-05-10 20:55:46.921628+00'),
	('6e2e8c5f-ecb9-4508-8f80-ecd90f5ccf0a', '7e900716-2bec-4758-a757-d1d0dd31b316', 'sevt_01EgJD3bbcKmxbW43Z2KgpRN', 'span.model_request_end', '{"id": "sevt_01EgJD3bbcKmxbW43Z2KgpRN", "type": "span.model_request_end", "is_error": false, "model_usage": {"input_tokens": 6, "output_tokens": 222, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 8531}, "processed_at": "2026-05-10T20:55:45.668Z", "model_request_start_id": "sevt_01ToP4Pzc8rzL6af3F8tMrSw"}', '2026-05-10 20:55:45.668+00', '2026-05-10 20:55:46.921628+00'),
	('e3537faa-5fbd-4522-a310-b4738bb362e5', '7e900716-2bec-4758-a757-d1d0dd31b316', 'sevt_01FwRncqJPqvWz38cdZi6dgC', 'agent.tool_result', '{"id": "sevt_01FwRncqJPqvWz38cdZi6dgC", "type": "agent.tool_result", "content": [{"text": "1\t---\n2\tname: pptx\n3\tdescription: >\n4\t  Use this skill whenever a .pptx file is involved in any way — as input,\n5\t    output, or both.\n6\t  \n7\t    This includes:\n8\t    - Creating presentations, slide decks, or pitch decks\n9\t    - Reading, parsing, or extracting content from .pptx files\n10\t    - Editing or updating existing presentations\n11\t    - Combining or splitting slide decks\n12\t    - Working with templates, layouts, speaker notes, or comments\n13\t  \n14\t    Trigger this skill whenever the user mentions:\n15\t    - “deck”\n16\t    - “slides”\n17\t    - “presentation”\n18\t    - Any .pptx filename\n19\t  \n20\t    If a .pptx file needs to be opened, created, modified, or analyzed, use this skill.\n21\t---\n22\t\n23\t# PPTX Skill\n24\t\n25\t## Quick Reference\n26\t\n27\t| Task | Command / Guide |\n28\t|---|---|\n29\t| Read or analyze content | `python -m markitdown presentation.pptx` |\n30\t| Edit or create from template | See [editing.md](editing.md) |\n31\t| Create from scratch | See [pptxgenjs.md](pptxgenjs.md) |\n32\t\n33\t---\n34\t\n35\t# Reading Content\n36\t\n37\t## Extract Text\n38\t\n39\t```bash\n40\tpython -m markitdown presentation.pptx\n41\t```\n42\t\n43\t## Generate Slide Thumbnails\n44\t\n45\t```bash\n46\tpython scripts/thumbnail.py presentation.pptx\n47\t```\n48\t\n49\t## Unpack Raw XML\n50\t\n51\t```bash\n52\tpython scripts/office/unpack.py presentation.pptx unpacked/\n53\t```\n54\t\n55\t# Editing Workflow\n56\t\n57\tSee [editing.md](editing.md) for full details.\n58\t\n59\tTypical workflow:\n60\t1. Analyze the template with thumbnail.py\n61\t2. Unpack the presentation\n62\t3. Modify slides and content\n63\t4. Clean artifacts/placeholders\n64\t5. Repack the deck\n65\t\n66\t# Creating Presentations from Scratch\n67\t\n68\tSee [pptxgenjs.md](pptxgenjs.md) for full details.\n69\t\n70\tUse this approach when:\n71\t* No template exists\n72\t* No reference deck is available\n73\t* A fully custom presentation is needed\n74\t\n75\t# Design Guidance\n76\t\n77\t## Core Principles\n78\t\n79\t### Avoid Generic Slides\n80\t\n81\tDo not create plain bullet lists on white backgrounds. Every slide should feel intentionally designed.\n82\t\n83\t### Use a Topic-Specific Color Palette\n84\t\n85\tChoose colors that match the subject matter. If the same palette works equally well for unrelated topics, it is probably too generic.\n86\t\n87\t### Establish Visual Hierarchy\n88\t\n89\t* One dominant color should carry 60–70% of the visual weight\n90\t* Use 1–2 supporting colors\n91\t* Reserve a strong accent color for emphasis\n92\t\n93\t### Maintain Consistent Visual Motifs\n94\t\n95\tPick one reusable design element and repeat it throughout the deck, such as:\n96\t* Rounded image frames\n97\t* Colored icon circles\n98\t* Thick side borders\n99\t* Consistent card treatments\n100\t\n101\t### Consider a \"Sandwich\" Structure\n102\t\n103\tA common pattern:\n104\t* Dark title slide\n105\t* Light content slides\n106\t* Dark conclusion slide\n107\t\n108\tOr commit fully to a dark theme for a premium look.\n109\t\n110\t## Suggested Color Palettes\n111\t\n112\t| Theme | Primary | Secondary | Accent |\n113\t|---|---|---|---|\n114\t| Midnight Executive | #1E2761 | #CADCFC | #FFFFFF |\n115\t| Forest & Moss | #2C5F2D | #97BC62 | #F5F5F5 |\n116\t| Coral Energy | #F96167 | #F9E795 | #2F3C7E |\n117\t| Warm Terracotta | #B85042 | #E7E8D1 | #A7BEAE |\n118\t| Ocean Gradient | #065A82 | #1C7293 | #21295C |\n119\t| Charcoal Minimal | #36454F | #F2F2F2 | #212121 |\n120\t| Teal Trust | #028090 | #00A896 | #02C39A |\n121\t| Berry & Cream | #6D2E46 | #A26769 | #ECE2D0 |\n122\t| Sage Calm | #84B59F | #69A297 | #50808E |\n123\t| Cherry Bold | #990011 | #FCF6F5 | #2F3C7E |\n124\t\n125\t## Slide Layout Ideas\n126\t\n127\tEvery slide should contain a meaningful visual element:\n128\t* Images\n129\t* Charts\n130\t* Icons\n131\t* Shapes\n132\t* Diagrams\n133\t\n134\tAvoid text-only slides.\n135\t\n136\t### Common Layout Patterns\n137\t\n138\t* Two-column layouts\n139\t* Icon + text rows\n140\t* 2×2 or 2×3 grids\n141\t* Half-bleed image layouts\n142\t* Overlay text on imagery\n143\t\n144\t### Effective Data Presentation\n145\t\n146\t* Large statistic callouts\n147\t* Side-by-side comparisons\n148\t* Timelines and process flows\n149\t* Numbered sequences\n150\t\n151\t### Visual Polish\n152\t\n153\t* Icons inside colored circles\n154\t* Accent typography\n155\t* Consistent spacing\n156\t* Intentional whitespace\n157\t\n158\t## Typography\n159\t\n160\t### Recommended Font Pairings\n161\t\n162\t| Header Font | Body Font |\n163\t|---|---|\n164\t| Georgia | Calibri |\n165\t| Arial Black | Arial |\n166\t| Calibri | Calibri Light |\n167\t| Cambria | Calibri |\n168\t| Trebuchet MS | Calibri |\n169\t| Impact | Arial |\n170\t| Palatino | Garamond |\n171\t| Consolas | Calibri |\n172\t\n173\t### Recommended Sizes\n174\t\n175\t| Element | Size |\n176\t|---|---|\n177\t| Slide title | 36–44 pt bold |\n178\t| Section header | 20–24 pt bold |\n179\t| Body text | 14–16 pt |\n180\t| Captions | 10–12 pt |\n181\t\n182\t### Spacing Guidelines\n183\t\n184\t* Minimum margins: 0.5\"\n185\t* Gap between content blocks: 0.3\"–0.5\"\n186\t* Leave adequate breathing room\n187\t* Avoid overfilling slides\n188\t\n189\t## Common Mistakes to Avoid\n190\t\n191\t* Repeating the same layout on every slide\n192\t* Center-aligning body text\n193\t* Weak size contrast between headings and body copy\n194\t* Defaulting to generic blue palettes\n195\t* Inconsistent spacing\n196\t* Styling only a few slides while leaving others plain\n197\t* Creating text-only slides\n198\t* Forgetting text box padding\n199\t* Using low-contrast text or icons\n200\t* Overly narrow text boxes causing awkward wrapping\n201\t\n202\t### Important\n203\t\n204\tNever use decorative accent lines under slide titles. This is a strong indicator of low-quality AI-generated slides.\n205\t\n206\tUse whitespace, typography, or color blocking instead.\n207\t\n208\t# QA Process (Required)\n209\t\n210\tAssume the first render contains issues.\n211\tYour job is to actively find and fix them.\n212\t\n213\t## Content QA\n214\t\n215\t### Extract and Review Text\n216\t\n217\t```bash\n218\tpython -m markitdown output.pptx\n219\t```\n220\t\n221\tCheck for:\n222\t* Missing content\n223\t* Typos\n224\t* Incorrect slide order\n225\t* Formatting issues\n226\t\n227\t### Detect Placeholder Content\n228\t\n229\t```bash\n230\tpython -m markitdown output.pptx | grep -iE \"xxxx|lorem|ipsum|this.*(page|slide).*layout\"\n231\t```\n232\t\n233\tIf any results appear, remove or replace them before finalizing.\n234\t\n235\t## Visual QA\n236\t\n237\t### Required Workflow\n238\t\n239\tConvert slides to images and inspect them visually.\n240\t\n241\t### Convert Slides to Images\n242\t\n243\t```bash\n244\tpython scripts/office/soffice.py --headless --convert-to pdf output.pptx\n245\tpdftoppm -jpeg -r 150 output.pdf slide\n246\tls slide-*.jpg\n247\t```\n248\t\n249\tNote:\n250\t* slide-1.jpg for decks under 10 slides\n251\t* slide-01.jpg for 10–99 slides\n252\t* slide-001.jpg for 100+ slides\n253\t\n254\tUse the exact filenames returned by ls.\n255\t\n256\t### Visual Inspection Checklist\n257\t\n258\tLook for:\n259\t* Overlapping elements\n260\t* Text overflow or clipping\n261\t* Misaligned decorative elements\n262\t* Footer collisions\n263\t* Uneven spacing\n264\t* Elements too close together\n265\t* Insufficient margins\n266\t* Inconsistent alignment\n267\t* Low-contrast text or icons\n268\t* Excessive text wrapping\n269\t* Leftover placeholders\n270\t\n271\t### Suggested Review Prompt\n272\t\n273\t```\n274\tVisually inspect these slides. Assume there are issues — find them.\n275\t\n276\tLook for:\n277\t- Overlapping elements\n278\t- Text overflow\n279\t- Alignment problems\n280\t- Uneven spacing\n281\t- Low contrast\n282\t- Placeholder content\n283\t- Clipping or cutoff text\n284\t\n285\tFor each slide, report all issues found, including minor ones.\n286\t```\n287\t\n288\t### Verification Loop\n289\t\n290\t1. Generate slides\n291\t2. Convert to images\n292\t3. Inspect carefully\n293\t4. List issues\n294\t5. Fix issues\n295\t6. Re-render affected slides\n296\t7. Re-check for new problems\n297\t\n298\tDo not declare success until at least one full fix-and-verify cycle is complete.\n299\t\n300\t### Re-Render Individual Slides\n301\t\n302\t```bash\n303\tpdftoppm -jpeg -r 150 -f N -l N output.pdf slide-fixed\n304\t```\n305\t\n306\tReplace N with the slide number.\n307\t\n308\t# Dependencies\n309\t\n310\t## Python Packages\n311\t\n312\t```bash\n313\tpip install \"markitdown[pptx]\"\n314\tpip install Pillow\n315\t```\n316\t\n317\t## Node Package\n318\t\n319\t```bash\n320\tnpm install -g pptxgenjs\n321\t```\n322\t\n323\t## System Dependencies\n324\t\n325\t* LibreOffice (soffice) — PDF conversion\n326\t* Poppler (pdftoppm) — PDF to image conversion\n", "type": "text"}], "is_error": false, "tool_use_id": "sevt_01MqrBSdgDE3uBrU47LFgws2", "processed_at": "2026-05-10T20:55:58.918Z"}', '2026-05-10 20:55:58.918+00', '2026-05-10 20:56:02.641661+00'),
